{"id":7690,"date":"2017-10-22T12:19:13","date_gmt":"2017-10-22T19:19:13","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/?p=7690"},"modified":"2025-08-15T04:10:42","modified_gmt":"2025-08-15T11:10:42","slug":"goat-range-3","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/2017\/10\/22\/goat-range-3\/","title":{"rendered":"GOAT RANGE"},"content":{"rendered":"<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\"><strong>Goat Range.\u00a0<\/strong>Boundaries are Kuskanax and Poplar Creeks on the north, Seaton Creek and Kaslo River on the south, the Slocan Valley on the west and Lardeau Creek and Kootenay Lake on the east.<br \/>\nMaps: 82K\/3 Roseberry, 82K\/6 Poplar Creek, 82K\/2 Lardeau, 82K\/7 Duncan Lake, 82K\/4 Nakusp, and 82k\/5 Trout Lake.<br \/>\nThe glaciers have undergone considerable retreat in the 20<sup>th<\/sup>\u00a0century. There is a large healthy glacier on the NE side of Mt Cooper, the only peak that exceeds 3000m. The area around Whitewater Creek, Marten Mountain, Mount Dolly Varden and Mount Cooper are all grizzly bear habitat.<br \/>\nThe entire area was a centre of mining exploration and activity around the turn of the century. Everything (including Mt Cooper) between the Slocan River and the Kootenay-Duncan system had been climbed before 1925.<br \/>\nAccess to Goat Range Provincial Park is virtually impossible as all access roads have had all their bridges removed and have become very overgrown. It is critical wildlife habitat for mountain caribou and grizzly bear.\u00a0<\/span><\/p>\n<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\"><a style=\"color: #000000;\" href=\"http:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/2017\/10\/18\/goat-range\/\">Goat Range<\/a><a style=\"color: #000000;\" href=\"http:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/2017\/10\/18\/goat-range\/\"><strong><br \/>\n<\/strong><\/a><strong><a style=\"color: #000000;\" href=\"http:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/2017\/10\/18\/goat-range-provincial-park\/\">GOAT RANGE PROVINCIAL PARK<\/a><\/strong><\/span><\/p>\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><img decoding=\"async\" class=\"alignleft\" src=\"https:\/\/www.spacesfornature.org\/greatspaces\/images\/maps\/goatrange2.gif\" alt=\"goatrange2.gif (520\u00d7512)\" \/><\/span><\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p>&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><br \/>\n\u0394 <a style=\"color: #000000;\" href=\"http:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/2017\/10\/16\/unnamed-deception\/\">UN (Deception) 2660m, UN (Bosworth) 2700m<\/a><br \/>\n\u0394 <a style=\"color: #000000;\" href=\"http:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/2017\/10\/16\/triple-peaks\/\">Triple Peaks, Mt Emmens<\/a><\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\">\u0394<sup>K<\/sup>\u00a0<a style=\"color: #000000;\" href=\"http:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/2017\/10\/16\/cascade-mountain\/\">Cascade Mt<\/a><\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\">\u0394<sup>K<\/sup>\u00a0<a style=\"color: #000000;\" href=\"http:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/2017\/10\/16\/mount-marion\/\">Mt Marion<\/a><\/span><br \/>\n<span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\">\u0394\u00a0<a style=\"color: #000000;\" href=\"http:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/2017\/10\/16\/mount-cooper-un-2640\/\">Mt<\/a><a style=\"color: #000000;\" href=\"http:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/2017\/10\/16\/mount-cooper-un-2640\/\">\u00a0Coop<\/a><a style=\"color: #000000;\" href=\"http:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/2017\/10\/16\/mount-cooper-un-2640\/\">er<\/a><a style=\"color: #000000;\" href=\"http:\/\/www.ronperrier.net\/2017\/10\/16\/mount-cooper-un-2640\/\">\u00a0&amp; UN 2640<\/a><br \/>\n\u0394 <a style=\"color: #000000;\" title=\"MEADOW MOUNTAIN\" href=\"https